That is what version is installed on your computer.

Cross-posting from the TexturesUnlimited OP --

--------------------------------------------------------

Requirements:

TexturesUnlimited currently requires the use of the either the DirectX11 or OpenGL-Core graphics API.  This may be activated by using the '-force-glcore' and/or '-force-d3d11' command line options to launch KSP.

Other graphics APIs will 'work' (DX9, legacy GL), but will have rendering errors.

--------------------------------------------------------

You could try using either DX11 or OpenGL mode and see if the problem persists.  Notes regarding Unity command line switches can be found here -- https://docs.unity3d.com/Manual/CommandLineArguments.html

@KSPFanatic102 and @Shadowmage

From looking at the GameData folder I picked out a few likely candidates and found a conflict between TU and the @RangeMachine build of Texture Replacer which is likely being used for visor reflections. I can recall you being in discussion with the TRR folks about how to proceed with certain aspects of handling reflections to prevent issues so I don't know if anything can be done here.

This may only be a part of the issue though since my flag rendered correctly unlike the screenshot provided. That could be down to the other TU config pack though if that was still present I guess.

I also noticed something funky with Kronal Vessel Viewer that I'll investigate a bit more when I get the time but in that case, I suspect it might be that TU breaks the KVV preview.

 

Edit: Scrub that, DX11 breaks KVV.

Interesting... wish I had more time... as that is likely something I could (help) fix.

 

4 hours ago, Manwith Noname said:

I can recall you being in discussion with the TRR folks about how to proceed with certain aspects of handling reflections to prevent issues so I don't know if anything can be done here.

I was for awhile yes, and we came to the conclusion that everything they needed to make a change-over to using the TU shaders and reflection system was already in place, and would have required only very minor changes to the codebase for TR (like only one or two lines..).  I'm not sure what happened past that point that would have prevented them from making the changes.... but apparently it didn't happen for one reason or another.

(again, if I had more time, I'd put together a PR to see if I could help speed the process along....)

@Shadowmage

The thing with Texture Replacer is there are several builds out in the wild. The original author hadn't updated it in a while so others started doing it. You were discussing things with the people who look after Texture Replacer Replaced which sort of became the unofficial official replacement if only because it had an actual release thread. When 1.4 broke the reflection shader they spoke with you, meanwhile Rangemachine who had been maintaining another fork got things working in 1.4 with reflection. At the same time, Shaw came back and updated the original fork and CydonianMonk released DIRT (a simplified texture replacer fork).

Heh, so basically, Texture Replacer has become somewhat difficult to keep tabs on in a way. I didn't fully test it but Shaw's build of TR didn't cause the problem. It was only when I added RangeMachine's build that I got the wonky half applied shader.

@Manwith Noname  That might explain what happened then   I'm still willing to help them sort it all out, but would need to know who to speak with, and they would need to be willing to make some minor code-side changes to switch over to using the TU shaders.   (The biggest/only real change would be to change from using Shader.Find() to looking through GameDatabase.loadedShaders list in order to find the shaders to use...)
